For those who do not understand climate change: IT IS SCIENCE NOT POLITICS.
1) Light heats up the planet
2) Light will interact with the electrons on molecules. Most atmospheric molecules do NOT reflect light (like oxygen) but CO2 DOES causing what is called the greenhouse gas effect.
3) There is natural, balanced system of the carbon exchange system.

Humans breathing out CO2 and plants "breathing" it in to make it O2 (Photosynthesis and Repiration)
AND carbon on the surface of earth (carbon atoms in animals, plants, etc.) sedimenting onto the ground to later become rock shot out by a volcano or eroded into our atmosphere (sedementation-volcano,weathering). We have set of the imbalance in favor of increase of CO2 in atmosphere.

For the benefit of those who don't live near Polar bears, polar bears don't always live on ice, way up in the Arctic. It is quite normal for them to venture down past Hudson's Bay into Northern Ontario or Quebec, and they live all throughout Northern Canada, a lot of these areas are certainly not the endless ice that polar bears live on, in the Arctic.

TL;DR It's normal for polar bears to be nowhere near ice, it doesn't mean global warming per se, it means they traveled south.

There is no evidence that this starving bear was a ‚Äúvictim‚Äù of sea ice loss caused by global warming.

SeaLegacy co-founder Cristina Mittermeier (whose organization filmed the bear) later said in an interview that the reason the bear died was ‚Äúirrelevent‚Äù ‚Äî essentially admitting that she was using this poor individual as a serendipitous photo op to illustrate the future fate she imagines for all bears.

‚ÄúIt is impossible to tell why he was in this state. Maybe it could‚Äôve been because of an injury or disease,‚Äù Mittermeier said.

Research done by polar bear specialsts that work in the field shows that the most common natural cause of death for polar bears is starvation, resulting from one cause or another (too young, too old, injured, sick) (Amstrup 2003):

‚ÄúStarvation of independent young as well as very old animals must account for much of the natural mortality among polar bears‚Ä¶ Also, age structure data show that subadults aged 2-5years survive at lower rates than adults (Amstrup 1995), probably because they are still learning hunting and survival skills.‚Äù

‚ÄúI once observed a 3-year-old subadult that weighed only 70 kg in November. This was near the end of the autumn period in which Beaufort Sea bears reach their peak weights (Durner and Amstrup 1996), and his cohorts at that time weighed in excess of 200 kg. This young animal apparently had not learned the skills needed to survive and was starving to death.‚Äù

A lot of people here don't seem to understand the situation. *The goal of this short film was not to prove climate change and it was not say that every polar bear are in this situation right now too.* This short film tells the story of the future (in few decades) for every individual polar bear if we continue to act like we are. Right now the populations are stable on the whole since 1 or 2 years. It doesn‚Äôt change the fact that they are a lot less than a decade ago. But the climate is warming and so the ice is melting, particularly there in the North Pole. Because of that in the next decades the habitat of the polar bear wills disappears. *And as their habitat will disappear every polar bear will starve to death like the one this film!* It will be a slow, horrible and unstoppable death/extinction. *We cannot feed them.* Feeding will only make it worse and cause aggression near villages. So there is only one way to save them and it‚Äôs by stopping the climate change. And for the ones that though it was an old bear, it is not. *This bear is young, or I should say was because it's dead now.*

This video would have you believe the lack of ice has killed this animal (it mentions ice free land in the video description). It's not the lack of ice or lack of cold that has killed this animal. If it was a lack of the climate, you wouldn't see this bear in North American zoos all over the place in the dead of summer. What you are seeing here is a polar bear that is old or has suffered from some injury at some point. I would like to see the unedited video in regular speed rather than slo mode. The bear at one point seems to have a very serious limp as if it has a damaged back left leg. If this animal sustained an injury, then it won't be able to chase down prey, or move to where the prey has gone. I'm not going to deny that the environment has changed, but the environment (or lack thereof) did not cause that bear to die. If the food moved, the bear could move with it. Happens all the time during migrations. This video is being used to mislead/manipulate.

If you want to do your part then do your part, but my point is that with or without a carbon tax, AI, increasing our dependency on technology, oil, etc. the changes will still happen. No matter what we do there will be fires, tornadoes, hurricanes and other extreme weather occurrences. No matter what we do the ice will melt and the sea level will rise. We can move, we can adapt, we can try to help save lives, but we shouldn't waste time and resources trying to sustain the infrastructure we know is collapsing or the industries and systems or institutions that are corrupt, collapsing and unsustainable. Places like Puerto Rico, should just be abandoned and the people relocated. We don't have to keep developing, keep building new roads and highways and keep exploiting resources, but nobody is willing to sacrifice their luxury or convenience and live simpler more humble lifestyles. A lot of people here don't seem to understand the situation. The goal of this short film was not to prove climate change and it was not say that every polar bear are in this situation right now too. This short film tells the story of the future (in few decades) for every individual polar bear if we continue to act like we are.

Right now the populations are stable on the whole since 1 or 2 years. It doesn‚Äôt change the fact that they are a lot less than a decade ago.
But the climate is warming and so the ice is melting, particularly there in the North Pole. Because of that in the next decades the habitat of the polar bear wills disappear. And as their habitat will disappear every polar bear will starve to death like the one this film! It will be a slow, horrible and unstoppable death/extinction.

We cannot feed them. Feeding will only make it worse and cause aggression near villages. So there is only one way to save them and it‚Äôs by stopping the climate change.

Power and control, you dimwit: (Hint: Google carbon credit... pretty soon they will tax your breath.) Under the Kyoto Protocol, the 'caps' or quotas for Greenhouse gases for the developed Annex 1 countries are known as Assigned Amounts and are listed in Annex B. The quantity of the initial assigned amount is denominated in individual units, called Assigned amount units (AAUs), each of which represents an allowance to emit one metric tonne of carbon dioxide equivalent, and these are entered into the country's national registry. In turn, these countries set quotas on the emissions of installations run by local business and other organizations, generically termed 'operators'. Countries manage this through their national registries, which are required to be validated and monitored for compliance by the UNFCCC. Each operator has an allowance of credits, where each unit gives the owner the right to emit one metric tonne of carbon dioxide or other equivalent greenhouse gas. Operators that have not used up their quotas can sell their unused allowances as carbon credits, while businesses that are about to exceed their quotas can buy the extra allowances as credits, privately or on the open market. As demand for energy grows over time, the total emissions must still stay within the cap, but it allows industry some flexibility and predictability in its planning to accommodate this. By permitting allowances to be bought and sold, an operator can seek out the most cost-effective way of reducing its emissions, either by investing in 'cleaner' machinery and practices or by purchasing emissions from another operator who already has excess 'capacity'. Since 2005, the Kyoto mechanism has been adopted for CO2 trading by all the countries within the European Union under its European Trading Scheme (EU ETS) with the European Commission as its validating authority. From 2008, EU participants must link with the other developed countries who ratified Annex I of the protocol, and trade the six most significant anthropogenic greenhouse gases. In the United States, which has not ratified Kyoto, and Australia, whose ratification came into force in March 2008, similar schemes are being considered.

In an older animal these things will happen but not as much as we're seeing in the video and not in the same ways. The ribs, for instance, wouldn't be as pronounced as they are and the muscle around the torso would still be quite dense in an elder bear. Hope that clears some things up. I'm no expert, but I do know some about muscle deterioration and fur discolouration aging (dilution) genes. This bear is a young one.
